<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-31T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-31T16:00:00-05:00" n="346" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/26904: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vera Cruz</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wood</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vera
                                        Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-31T14:00:00-07:00"><hi rend="italic">January 31,
                                        1924—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 6:42
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Department’s telegram January 23, 5 p.m. All mines have been removed from
                            ports in question. Am informed by Mr. de la Huerta that Salina Cruz was
                            mined by Federal authorities. He feels that it was not asking too much
                            in view of the removal of this protection he had against an attack by
                            the Mexican gunboat <hi rend="italic">Bravo</hi> now at New Orleans to
                            entertain the hope that said gunboat will not be allowed to leave the
                            port of New Orleans during this conflict.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wood</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>